"/> Popping a cool top &amp; sharing my most recent ghost.........sorry it's
long.....but Vera, my ghost, insists upon her say.......

About five years ago, I disposed of the personal property portion of the
estate of a woman who, in the days of her youth &amp; beauty, was a vocalist
with big bands in the New York City area. This was a tag sale.
The house &amp; grounds were full of boxes &amp; bags of mixed trash &amp; treasure. I
was instructed by the court to look everywhere for a will which reputably
existed solely for the purpose of preventing her ex-husband from laying
claim to certain memorabilia that the lady most definitely did not want him
to have.
All of her friends knew that the will existed. No one knew where it was.
Therefore I dared throw not even a personal letter away without checking the
contents.
I grew to know the lady well. (I grew to like the lady, as well)
She kept all of her publicity pics etc. &amp; in many of them she was wearing a
gorgeous white fox stole.
I found the white fox stole hanging in one of the closets, carefully
enclosed in the proper storage material.
As the time begin to run out &amp; I still had much to tag &amp; had not found the
will either, I begin to work evenings.
One night I smelled an overpowering &amp; heavy odor of perfume, found no
source, &amp; opened the windows to air out. Of course, I closed them &amp; locked
up carefully as I left for the night. The lawyer &amp; I had the only keys to
the house. We had the locks changed when I started tagging the contents.
When I returned in the morning, the white fox stole was laid grandly out on
the bed in front bedroom,. The bag it had been in remained in the closet at
the other end of the house.
That evening, as dusk closed in &amp; I flipped the first light inside the
house, the odor of perfume again begin to fill the house. I made a
considered, judicious, unemotional decision to high-tail it out of there
immediately &amp; to forego any more evening hours in the house.
In the morning the fox stole was under the far corner of the bed. I had to
drag it out with a broomstick. On subsequent mornings it was found (1) on
the couch, (2) draped across the birdcage, (3) atop the refrigerator (at
least it wasn't stuffed in it) &amp; various other places.
I tried to joke about it, but I was growing a little uneasy with the
traveling stole, So in desperation, I decided to talk to Vera (its former
owner) about it.
&quot;Vera,&quot; I said aloud at three o'clock on a sunny afternoon, glancing at
shadowed corners, and feeling more than a little foolish, &quot;If that's your
ghost playing these games, give me some kind of clue of what you want, will
ya&quot;
&quot;Clunk&quot; A composition animated Christmas figure (German &amp; almost
life-sized) fell chock over, gently enough not to damage. Aha.....one of
the items that Vera most definitely did not want her ex-husband to have.
Feeling not quite so foolish as before, but a tad more desperate, as my
reality tried to redefine itself, I almost shouted, &quot;Gimme a break here,
Vera. I can't find your will. You know I'm trying. I'll bet you can't even
remember where you put it. So get off my back, will ya.&quot;
For the first time ever, the house suddenly took on that dense silence of a
truly uninhabited structure.
The fox stole never moved again. The ex-husband came to pick up the property
awarded by the court &amp; no heavy odor of perfume protested his presence. The
sale went smoothly &amp; profitably. A very pretty young lady purchased the fox
stole &amp; I don't thing Vera minded.
And now finally, as I quietly promised after my outburst, Vera has had, if
not her way, at least, her say, if only in cyberspace.
donnamel
