My Egbert...

by Tracy Doyle

Okay, some of you know that for years I have been researching the
turn-of-the-century pop music composer, Egbert Van Alstyne. If you'll
read the story at:
http://www.rag-time.com/fest/bio.html
... you will see my almost unnatural attachment to this fellow.

Anyhow, it's one thing to pick a biographical subject out of the blue
and later figure out that he is related to you. It's entirely another
when weird things start to happen which should not.

1.) I call a friend of mine who is a piano roll collector, out of the
blue, just to say &quot;hi.&quot; He says, &quot;I was just going to pick up the phone
to call you. I can't believe you're calling right now...&quot; Turns out he
had a piano roll auction list in his hand with a hand-played player
piano roll by Egbert called &quot;That Sneaky, Creepy Tune.&quot; I had never
heard of it before. Through my friend, I placed a bid and won it. Years
later, the manuscript turned up in the Library of Congress... after
years of having been missing.

2.) This all started about a year before I divorced my ex. He used to go
to work early in the morning, and I'd stay up late at night practicing
the piano. I was practicing one night, when I saw someone walk up to me
on my left. I thought it was Tom (the ex). I said, &quot;What are you doing
up at this hour?&quot; but as I turned to look, I realized no one was there.
I started playing again (of course, I was working up one of Egbert's
tunes)... and I saw that fellow again.. but when I looked up, he wasn't
there. Well, a few days later, the EX began to see a fellow peeking in
on me while we were watching TV in the den... He hasn't really left me
alone since, but he has been in a quite period lately.

3.) Within a few months, I was having plenty of &quot;Egbert moments...&quot;
events which should NOT have happened, statistically. Finding his
mother's divorce papers in a nearby courthouse... finding a transcript
of her actual testimony (from 1900) in another.. all within 10 minutes
of walking in the dcor. Calling people at the &quot;very moment&quot; they found
piano rolls or sheet music which I didn't have...

4.) But one of the two best Egbert moments was when S.O. and I were
listening to an LP of march music written by Sousa. The last track on
the side we were listening to was &quot;Liberty Bell.&quot; Well, the tune
finished playing, the tone arm lifted and swung back toward the cradle -
then swung back into the body of the record and landed EXACTLY at the
beginning of &quot;Liberty Bell.&quot; S.O., who has an engineering degree and
also is an expert in magic, couldn't believe it. &quot;That's IMPOSSIBLE!&quot; he
said. Yes, it was. Egbert wanted to hear it again, I think... funny, but
his early compositions were heavily influenced by Sousa and his then
&quot;right hand man,&quot; Arthur Pryor. Egbert and Pryor remianed friends for
years. There is more to that story....

5.) But I think the most astonishing thing was the last major &quot;Egbert moment...&quot;
I was at the grocery store, walking up and down the aisles with my
little cart. I turned down the aisle with the Italian food, and I was
thinking about my Egbert bio. There was only one other gal in the aisle
with me. I heard an abrasive sort of noise, like a jar or can sliding
over a rippled shelf. The sound had a very specific source -- both the
gal and I looked directly at the source of the noise. Then we saw it...
a jar of spaghetti sauce MOVED before our eyes. It slid toward the edge
of the shelf with a &quot;GRRTHTHTHTTTTT.&quot; She and I looked at each other...
another &quot;GRRRTTHTHTHTHTTTT...&quot; and it slid nearly half way off the
shelf. One more &quot;GRRTTHTHTHTHTTTT...&quot; and over the edge it went,
crashing to the floor and breaking!

She looked at me and said, &quot;I didn't do it!!&quot; I said, &quot;I know. We both
saw that, right?&quot; She said (eyes open quite wide) &quot;I saw it! GAWD, was
that WEIRD!! It's like someone else was here!&quot;

I said, &quot;Yep, I know... and don't even ask.&quot;

Frankly, these things don't even faze me anymore. They don't frighten
me. In a way, they comfort me. I've heard my recently dead cat purring
and felt my dead dog licking my face. It's all very strange, but in a
way very nice. I sure can't explain it, and I don't care to. I feel
priviledged to have had such experiences, and I hope they continue.

RAGards,

Tracy
