I probably shouldn't jump in here, what with all the good and serious
tales, but ....

This isn't exactly a ghost story, although it was for awhile. It
certainly raised my hackles -- and had me seriously doubting my sanity
for a period of about three weeks.

It was summer, and I was dozing in the dark on the living room couch,
some movie from AMC flickering on the TV. Something woke me, and as I
opened my eyes, I saw through the arch into the darkened dining room.
And saw the black silhouette of a cat gliding past the long table.

That was not unusual in our house, but then I looked down from the
couch, and there was our cat, peacefully asleep. He and I were both
good at that. I looked back to the dining room, saw nothing. But I
jumped up and went there. Nope, nothing.

A shadow? No, it was too perfectly the outline of a cat, and it
stayed in my mind. And then, one night the following week, I got up
from the couch and stepped around my fast-asleep cat to go through the
dining room and into the kitchen for the day's 32nd cup of coffee.
There in the dim, eating out of my cat's bowl, was that damned black
*something*!

We froze. And then the thing just flat out ... disappeared! By that
time, I was moving, running toward where it had been, around the
corner, down the short hall, back into the living room, through the
living room into the dining room. Back in the kitchen. Nothing.

I went through the entire house, rippling with goosebumps. The only
feline to be found was my blissfully deaf orange cat, there by the
couch. I checked the doors; everything shut. Next day, I went to
work in serious wonder. I didn't tell my wife. I didn't tell
anybody.

I was working nights then, and I usually got home at 3 or 4 a.m. And
I would sit and watch TV for awhile before going to bed. But now I
was scared to sit in my own living room. I was literally jumping at
shadows and thinking I might well be having mental troubles.

And then I saw the black blob again, this time oozing through the
dining room *toward* the kitchen. Son of a bitch!! I leaped up and
raced out there. Gone, of course. Nothing. But this time, I turned
on every light I could find. And I REALLY searched.

I spent a long time. And, finally, down on my hands and knees, I
found a tiny hole in the screen of the patio door. Not big enough for
more than a mouse, I thought. But I went to bed clinging to the hope.
I still hadn't told anyone.

I watched for the next several nights. And the eyestrain paid off.
Ridiculous. Sitting in the dark, watching for a figment of my
imagination. But there, finally ... there he was! Snaking himself
through the hole in the screen. Phew! Oh good!!

A real live cat, come to visit a full bowl of Friskies. Next day, I
took the screendoor to be fixed. And started to tell people my story.
Laughing, of course. Brave and sure of myself through it all ....

Marshall

