I too, have a couple of ghost stories to tell. The first one could be
nothing more than wishful thinking....the second one is a bit more
complicated and seen by both my husband and me and a few others.
I inherited my Grandmother's rocker....she was a diabetic, and later in her
life she developed terrible leg ulcers. To ease the pain, she would sit in
her chair and &quot;rock the pain away&quot; while telling stories, sorting buttons,
or making little spool dolls for her favorite grandaughters (my sister and I
were her only grandaughters, as well). I can remember many a night falling
to sleep in the featherbed, lulled by the squeak of Grandma's chair, rocking
back and forth, back and forth. After inheriting the chair, (and annoying my
parents to no end by not having it stripped and refinished so it would look
like a new chair)....there have been times, like when my children were
toddlers and had been deathly ill, when I know I've heard the chair squeak
as it rocked by itself. Unfortunately no one has heard it but me.....BUT,
after each of these times, many people have said they smelled a rich perfume
in the house......and Grandmother wore Topaz.
The second thing that happened was in our present home. It was built in the
year 1900 and thus will be officially 100 years old at the start of
2000.....the house has lots of quirks....the floors run dowhill in some
rooms.....rooms like the bathrooms are add-ons....and some of the extensions
were built by someone who had not a clue what a square was........but after
getting rid the old stationary heating source removed and installing
central air furnace....there was nary a cold spot, or ghostly presence,
other than the scent of Grandmother's perfume occasionally, in the entire
house. It wasn't an ominous house, just one that had seen a lot of families
come and go, and yet never seemed to retain any impression of them, except
on the surface. We raised our daughters, lived, laughed, and loved....and
have remodeled, trying to bring some kind of character to the old
house....and other than being a pleasant place to live, it pretty much
resisted our efforts. Until......
Nine years ago, Gary and I adopted two little boys to get them away from an
abusive situation. The baby was seven months old, and the oldest was a
little over two, ( he was nonverbal, and lived under our dining room table
for two weeks....but he's 11 now and doing wonderfully now)....it was hard
going from no kids at home, to having a baby and a toddler.....but it was
worth it. We got them settled in, but not more than a few days after they
came to stay, we started noticing something odd. After putting them to bed,
if you were sitting in the rocking chair or on the sofa, out of the corner
of your eye you'd see a little blond head peeking out of the bedroom
door.....but when you turned to look....nothing would be there!! I just felt
that it must be stress and that I was imagining it...but about three weeks
later while Gary and I were sitting on the sofa and I turned to see if Mark
had gotten out of bed, when Gary said, &quot;Have you been seeing it too?&quot;....It
turned out that Gary, my Mother-In-Law, my Sister, and a neighbor had all
seen this little boy, peeking out of doors and windows, dressed in a
nightshirt. I haven't been able to find any history of a child dying in our
house, though our neighbor insisted that a little boy died in the Spanish
Influenza outbreak, but I haven't been able to verify that. The little
ghost, or maybe guardian Angel stayed with the boys for, maybe, five years
or so.....but now that the boys are thriving and healthy, we haven't seen
him....maybe he doesn't feel the boys need him anymore.....but finally our
house feels like a home. Messy, cluttered with various toys and trucks and
video games....but at last alive.
There is my Chirstmas offering.....
Lois E.

