Long Island (we're in NH). It needed a bit of work and some &quot;freshening
up&quot;, but was livable, and had some nice antique features (pumpkin pine
panelling, central chimney, sloping floors, etc). We rented it for
another year, 'til the new owner moved up, and we bought our own
remuddled 1830's farmhouse (no ghosts here yet), during which the old
place deteriorated badly, and the new owner's &quot;fixes&quot; worsened matters
considerably. For instance the fill valve for the forced hot water heat
failed, and the lines froze - so he left the old valve in, decided we
didn't need heat in the kitchen or bedroom and cut out the loop that had
split in 20+ places so the rest could be used with no futher repair...
damp laundry would freeze in the washer (in the kitchen) overnight ;-)
Since we left, he's collapsed an addition (don't replace 8x8 timbers
with 2x6's, they don't hold well), ripped out the central chimney
(recently restored) and gutted the house. Today it stands a shell with
no back wall, no siding, a gaping hole in the roof - no life. I was
quite maliciously intrigued when recently a common acquiantance asked if
we'd ever had ghost problems in the 30+ years we lived there (never) -
he was very unsettled, and the same week someone else mentioned the
addition (?) had begun to collapse on the owner when he was in
there..... granted the structural damage is extensive, but if there ever
was a fitting occasion to wake the prior residents from the dead, I'd
